I can see I wasn't clear enough.  There are lots of features in
Leopard that require newish hardware to run.  But there are also lots
of features that could run on much older hardware just fine.  I'm
suggesting that there's a way for Apple to make the compatible
features available to owners of that older hardware.

In Windows there's DirectX 10, and you can run XP w/o it, but you
can't run some software w/o it.  But there is plenty of software that
will run w/o it.  And if you want DX10 support, you have to upgrade
your video card.

That's the kind of distinction I'm suggesting.  The features come with
the OS, and if you want them to run you have to have the hardware to
support it.  Customers should have a simple way to check if their
system supports the major feature in question and if it does, then
they can buy the software that requires it, as well as buy software
with the knowledge that the features they need will work even w/o
support for that major OS feature.

In the case of Leopard, I could see Core Animation requiring a minimum
CPU or Graphics card (or combination of the two).  And I think there's
enough detail in the &quot;Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard: the Ars Technica review&quot;
article to conclude that developers could write programs that would
work with or without Core Animation, and could set a flag to require
Core Animation if it was truly needed.  Most of the uses of Core
Animation suggested are for &quot;more visually appealing&quot; software
interaction.

Users of older Macs would be happier and would say things like, &quot;So
it's less appealing, at least I can still use it.&quot;

This would still mean that systems will become obsolete (unable to
upgrade), but they'd stay current longer and also live longer lives
since they'd become obsolete later. Therefore they'd provide more
customers to 3rd party developers, encourage a larger number of
software titles on the mac, and thus more potential customers for
Apple and all the developers.

