This isn't really about hardware.  From the developer's point of
view, it's all about software frameworks (the shared libraries
provided by Apple in the OS).  Many/most frameworks already
automagically use special hardware features if they're available, and
&quot;emulate&quot; the function if not.

The problem is that as frameworks advance, they do more and more - so
the programmer has to do less and less.  If the function is not
available in an older framework, then the programmer has only two
choices:  Don't support that older OS or write the whole thing
himself.

What you're suggesting is, in essence, for the programmer to pick a
least common denominator, and then never use anything more advanced.
That way the app can run on the older systems as well as the new,
without extra coding.  That's fine, if you want to ignore n years
worth of Apple's advances.

[This is why, back in the 80s, I used to support a particularly large
application that was written in FORTRAN II; the equivalent of driving
the flintmobile on a superhighway. FORTRAN II is from 1958, and was
replaced by FORTRAN IV in 1961.]

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;Users of older Macs would be happier and would say things like, &quot;So
&gt;it's less appealing, at least I can still use it.&quot;
">

sure.  But how is it worth the programmer's time to cater to that 1%
