Larry,

My comment was in the context of changing the equation of what's
required to upgrade to a new OS, so the requirements for running new
software would change too.

I was trying to explain my idea in an email and have come to the
conclusion that it's just too big, involving too many variables to
completely explain.  The point is that Apple has forced the Leopard
installer to refuse to install on machines that don't have at least an
867 MHz CPU, and I think they could change their approach so they
could keep those customers current for the same upgrade price instead
of forcing them to choose between buying a whole new computer and just
staying obsolete.

My speculation is that the overwhelming majority of Leopard would run
on significantly lesser hardware, and there are only a few of the
major features of Leopard that would have to be disabled on those
computers to make it happen.

Maybe the point should be that if 3rd party developers were to commit
to developing for Panther (10.2), and their software would work in
Tiger and Leopard too, then those customers wouldn't be obsolete.  I
suspect that a lot of software could be developed that way and it
would just work even better in Leopard.  But we all know it's better
if everyone can upgrade to the latest OS.

So in my ideal world, everyone would upgrade to leopard, and based on
their hardware, certain features would be enabled, such as Spotlight,
Core Animation, and Time Machine.  If your hardware could handle the
basics of the OS, then you'd check an &quot;Enabled Features&quot; panel to see
what features are enabled.  Older hardware can be kept current, but
would lack some features.  Programmers could disable groups of
features and test their software, then add support for features that
would enhance their products, but they'd still be functional on lesser
hardware unless their software absolutely required some feature, like
DVD Burning.  This is the best short explanation I can come up with,
and since we're not likely to influence Apple with comments on this
list, I don't wish to expend the effort to write more about it unless
a publisher or someone is willing to pay for my opinion.  Don't get me
wrong, I love helping others with free advice.  I just feel this has
gone way beyond that, and it's my own fault for bringing it up.

So I'd like to politely stop encouraging it now.  If you all wish to
make comments and/or discuss it among yourselves, feel free, just
kindly forgive me for bowing out of future comments on this subject.

